---
import CaseStudyLayout from "../../../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro";
import CalloutColumn from "../../../components/sections/CalloutColumn.astro";
import ContentSection from "../../../components/sections/ContentSection.astro";
import CalloutBlock from "../../../components/sections/CalloutBlock.astro";
import InfoCardGrid from "../../../components/sections/InfoCardGrid.astro";
import MediaSection from "../../../components/sections/MediaSection.astro";
import SectionIntro from "../../../components/sections/SectionIntro.astro";
import SurfaceCard from "../../../components/sections/SurfaceCard.astro";
import MicroLabel from "../../../components/typography/MicroLabel.astro";
import CardTitle from "../../../components/typography/CardTitle.astro";
import { getCaseStudyCardData, getMoreCaseStudyCards } from "../../../data/caseStudies";
import { resolveStaticAssetUrl as asset } from "../../../lib/assetUrl";

const caseStudy = getCaseStudyCardData("trackoff", "en");
const moreCaseStudies = getMoreCaseStudyCards("trackoff", "en");
---

<CaseStudyLayout
	title={`${caseStudy.title} | Design Case Study | Dmitry Shkaev`}
	description={caseStudy.description}
	pageTitle={caseStudy.title}
	heroSrc="/images/case-studies/trackoff/trackoff-hero.jpg"
	heroAlt="TrackOFF case study hero image"
	moreCaseStudies={moreCaseStudies}
>

		<ContentSection title="Company and team" bodyClass="mt-6">
			<p>
				TrackOFF was a consumer privacy company headquartered in Baltimore,
				Maryland (USA). Founded by <a
					href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/chandler-givens-42a6184/"
					target="_blank"
					rel="noreferrer"
					class="text-link text-stone-950"
				>Chandler Givens</a> and <a
					href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/ryan-flach-1647b1ba/"
					target="_blank"
					rel="noreferrer"
					class="text-link text-stone-950"
				>Ryan Flach</a>, it grew rapidly over the following four years. I
				joined the startup as <strong class="font-bold text-stone-950"
					>employee number two</strong
				>, and helped build the company from
				the very beginning. By the end of 2019, our team had 30+ beautiful
				people on board, many of whom I still call my friends.
			</p>
		</ContentSection>

		<ContentSection title="My role">
				<p>
					I was responsible for a wide range of projects <strong
						class="font-bold text-stone-950">covering all the company's
						needs</strong
					>. This work included designing UX &amp; UI for our
					website and software products on desktop and mobile, developing brand
					identity, creating visuals for hundreds of presentations, emails, and
					pitch decks, and doing print and physical design such as product
					packaging and in-store banners.
				</p>
				<p class="border-l border-stone-200 pl-4 text-[1.08rem] leading-[1.68] text-stone-950 sm:text-[1.16rem]">
					Having high responsibility, real deadlines, and a genuinely
					fast-paced environment while caring about every facet of the work was
					a <span class="font-bold">perfect bootcamp</span> that allowed me to
					grow and develop as a professional in record time.
				</p>
				<p>
					In hindsight, it was pretty hardcore, considering I was the only
					designer on the team for well over a year. Once we realized we were
					spreading ourselves thin, we brought <a
						href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/jon-schubbe-327aa613/"
						target="_blank"
						rel="noreferrer"
						class="text-link text-stone-950"
					>Jon Schubbe</a> on board to help with UX design, a man with whom I
					proceeded to work closely for the next 5 years.
				</p>
		</ContentSection>

		<MediaSection
			src={asset("/images/case-studies/trackoff/trackoff-team.jpg")}
			alt="TrackOFF team and office visuals"
		/>

		<ContentSection title="Website">
				<p>
					It all started with the TrackOFF website. Back in 2015, I was doing
					freelance work and took on a small project for Chandler to update the
					fold on the homepage. He liked both the results and how we clicked
					together, so I began to work on the designs for the rest of the site.
					We rapidly iterated and launched it within a month.
				</p>
				<p>
					Over the next few years we designed and launched <strong
						class="font-bold text-stone-950">three major versions</strong
					>
					of the website, evolving the branding and style, as well as
					constantly optimizing information architecture, acquisition funnels,
					and click-through rates.
				</p>
		</ContentSection>

		<MediaSection
			src={asset("/images/case-studies/trackoff/trackoff-product.png")}
			alt="TrackOFF product interfaces on desktop and mobile"
		/>

		<ContentSection title="Product" bodyClass="mt-6 space-y-4">
				<p>
					TrackOFF was the company's flagship product and the one that gave the
					business its name. It was a desktop-first privacy app designed to
					make online tracking far less reliable by obfuscating the digital
					signals websites and ad platforms used to profile people.
				</p>
			<InfoCardGrid class="mt-8" columnsClass="sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-2">
				<SurfaceCard padding="compact">
					<MicroLabel>Core value</MicroLabel>
					<p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-6 text-stone-700 sm:text-[0.95rem]">
						Reduced the accuracy of third-party profiling and cross-site
						tracking, giving users more privacy and a stronger sense of control
						over their browsing.
					</p>
				</SurfaceCard>
				<SurfaceCard padding="compact">
					<MicroLabel>Platforms</MicroLabel>
					<p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-6 text-stone-700 sm:text-[0.95rem]">
						Microsoft Windows, with millions of copies sold across distribution
						channels, later expanding to macOS, Android, and iOS.
					</p>
				</SurfaceCard>
			</InfoCardGrid>
			<div class="mt-8 grid gap-8 lg:grid-cols-3">
				<CalloutColumn
					title="What it did"
					titleClass="text-[1.15rem] sm:text-[1.3rem]"
					bodyClass="space-y-4"
				>
					<p>
						In simple terms, the product scrambled the identifying data a
						tracker could collect from a device. That made it much harder for
						data brokers and advertisers to confidently decide whether the
						user on one website was the same person they had seen elsewhere.
					</p>
				</CalloutColumn>
				<CalloutColumn
					title="Why it mattered"
					titleClass="text-[1.15rem] sm:text-[1.3rem]"
					bodyClass="space-y-4"
				>
					<p>
						By 2023, similar protections had become common in privacy-focused
						software and even mainstream browsers. Back in 2015, though, this
						was a genuinely forward-looking proposition that landed well as
						privacy awareness started to grow.
					</p>
				</CalloutColumn>
				<CalloutColumn
					title="My role in it"
					titleClass="text-[1.15rem] sm:text-[1.3rem]"
					bodyClass="space-y-4"
				>
					<p>
						When I joined, the interface lacked clarity, polish, and the kind
						of trust cues a privacy product needed. My job was to turn it into
						a product experience that felt understandable, credible, and
						usable across desktop first and later mobile surfaces.
					</p>
				</CalloutColumn>
			</div>
		</ContentSection>

		<MediaSection
			src={asset("/images/case-studies/trackoff/trackoff-marketing.png")}
			alt="TrackOFF marketing and promo materials"
		/>

		<ContentSection title="Marketing and promo materials" bodyClass="mt-6">
			<p>
				My responsibilities included creating marketing materials and
				presentations. We had a significant need for them, especially during
				our rapid growth phase. Having designed a ton of corporate newspapers
				and magazine layouts in the past, I saw it as one of the <strong
					class="font-bold text-stone-950">easier and more enjoyable</strong
				> parts of the job. The reason for that is probably the
				special feeling you have when you see a physical creation of yours,
				like a product box of your own design sitting on a store shelf, or a
				handout booklet in people's hands at a conference.
			</p>
		</ContentSection>

		<section class="mt-14 grid w-full gap-4 sm:gap-6">
			<div class="overflow-hidden rounded-[12px] bg-white/80 shadow-[0_1px_0_rgba(28,25,23,0.04)]">
				<img
					src={asset("/images/case-studies/trackoff/trackoff-promo-1.png")}
					alt="TrackOFF print and event collateral"
					class="h-auto w-full"
					loading="lazy"
				/>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="mt-12 w-full">
			<SectionIntro
				as="div"
				class="mt-0"
				title="Reseller portal and white-labelled products"
				bodyClass="max-w-4xl"
			>
				<p>
					To support reseller growth, I designed an internal portal that turned
					a clunky database-like workflow into a usable partner-facing tool for
					managing activation keys, renewals, and white-label product setups.
				</p>
			</SectionIntro>
			<div class="mt-8 grid gap-8 lg:grid-cols-[minmax(0,1.15fr)_minmax(0,0.85fr)] lg:items-start">
				<div class="space-y-7">
					<CalloutColumn title="Who it served">
						<p>
							Our reseller partners sold the product through their own
							channels, either under the TrackOFF brand or as white-label
							offers with their own logo and color scheme. I designed both the
							portal experience and the white-label UI variations that
							supported that model.
						</p>
					</CalloutColumn>
					<CalloutColumn title="What I designed">
						<p>
							The dashboard surfaced activation key status, expiration,
							renewals, and related details in a format that people could
							actually work with. It also supported bulk key generation, often
							at very large volumes, and included search tools for locating and
							managing groups of keys by category.
						</p>
					</CalloutColumn>
				</div>
				<CalloutBlock
					label="Outcome"
					title="A raw operational workflow became a much clearer partner product."
					class="max-w-none pl-4 lg:pl-8"
					bodyClass="text-sm leading-6 sm:text-[0.98rem] sm:leading-7"
				>
					<span slot="label-prefix" class="-translate-y-px text-amber-500">
							<svg
								xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
								viewBox="0 0 16 16"
								fill="currentColor"
								class="h-4 w-4"
								aria-hidden="true"
							>
								<path
									fill-rule="evenodd"
									d="M12 1.69a.494.494 0 0 0-.438-.494 32.352 32.352 0 0 0-7.124 0A.494.494 0 0 0 4 1.689v.567c-.811.104-1.612.24-2.403.406a.75.75 0 0 0-.595.714 4.5 4.5 0 0 0 4.35 4.622A3.99 3.99 0 0 0 7 8.874V10H6a1 1 0 0 0-1 1v2h-.667C3.597 13 3 13.597 3 14.333c0 .368.298.667.667.667h8.666a.667.667 0 0 0 .667-.667c0-.736-.597-1.333-1.333-1.333H11v-2a1 1 0 0 0-1-1H9V8.874a3.99 3.99 0 0 0 1.649-.876 4.5 4.5 0 0 0 4.35-4.622.75.75 0 0 0-.596-.714A30.897 30.897 0 0 0 12 2.256v-.567ZM4 3.768c-.49.066-.976.145-1.458.235a3.004 3.004 0 0 0 1.64 2.192A3.999 3.999 0 0 1 4 5V3.769Zm8 0c.49.066.976.145 1.458.235a3.004 3.004 0 0 1-1.64 2.192C11.936 5.818 12 5.416 12 5V3.769Z"
									clip-rule="evenodd"
								></path>
							</svg>
					</span>
					<p>
						That made the reseller model <strong class="font-bold text-stone-950">
							more attractive commercially
						</strong> and earned <strong class="font-bold text-stone-950">
							extremely positive feedback
						</strong> from existing partners about the improved process.
					</p>
				</CalloutBlock>
			</div>
		</section>

		<MediaSection
			src={asset("/images/case-studies/trackoff/trackoff-remote.jpg")}
			alt="TrackOFF remote collaboration and communication"
		/>

		<ContentSection title="Acquisition by Avast Software">
				<p>
					By the end of 2019, as we had been carving out a significant
					presence in the privacy software market, one of our largest partners
					offered to <a
						href="https://www.baltimoresun.com/business/bs-bz-trackoff-acquired-avast-20190531-story.html"
						target="_blank"
						rel="noreferrer"
						class="text-link text-stone-950"
					>acquire the company</a> and bring its key people on board. I was
					one of the specialists who were transferred under Avast's wing,
					allowing me to continue doing what I loved, now at a much larger
					scale.
				</p>
				<p>
					The TrackOFF app evolved to become Avast and AVG AntiTrack,
					immediately becoming <strong class="font-bold text-stone-950"
						>the most profitable product</strong
					> in Avast's entire software lineup at that time.
				</p>
		</ContentSection>

		<MediaSection
			src={asset("/images/case-studies/trackoff/trackoff-acquisition.jpg")}
			alt="TrackOFF acquisition and transition to Avast"
		/>

		<ContentSection title="Personal takeaway" bodyClass="mt-6">
			<p>
				Working at TrackOFF was an incredibly rewarding and memorable period,
				during which I made a lot of friends, and had a remarkable
				opportunity to grow as a generalist designer. Through this holistic
				experience, I gradually realized that <strong
					class="font-bold text-stone-950"
				>product design was the discipline where I could deliver the most
					value</strong>, so I focused on developing my skills in that field,
				making the transition to a larger company feel like a natural and
				purposeful next step.
			</p>
		</ContentSection>

</CaseStudyLayout>
